    <div class="section">
      <h3>CHIEF COMPLAINTS (CHRONOLOGICAL ORDER)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Redness in the eye</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Acute angle closure</li>
            <li>conjunctivitis</li>
            <li>sub conjunctival hemorrhage</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Pain in back of eye</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Scleritis</li>
            <li>keratitis</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Headahce</li>
        <li>Nausea and vomiting</li>
        <li>Discomfot/ itching in the eye</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Epi scleritis</li>
            <li>Allergic conjuntivitis</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Blurry vision</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Toxoplasmosis</li>
            <li>macular degeneraton</li>
            <li><br>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>loss of vision</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Open angle Glaucoms</li>
            <li>Retinal detachment</li>
            <li>hemianopioas</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>halos</li>
        <li>Floaters</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Toxoplasmosis</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Asx</li>
        <ol>
          <ol>
            <li>Open angle Glaucoms</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h4><br>
      </h4>
      <h4>1st COMPLAINT: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Redness</em> </h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Site:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
          which eye</li>
        <ul>
          <li>one eye</li>
          <li>both eye</li>
          <ul>
            <li>danger in Subconjunctival hemorrhage</li>
          </ul>
          <li>locaized <br>
            <ol>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>diffuse</li>
        </ul>
        <li>Onset: When did patient notice&nbsp;
          <ul>
            <li>Gradual</li>
            <li>Sudden (after trauma)</li>
            <ul>
              <ul>
                <li>Sub conjunctival hemorrhage</li>
              </ul>
            </ul>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Duration
          <ul>
            <li>&Acirc;&plusmn; Painlessness
              <ol>
                <li>Short = Inflammatory [Pain]</li>
                <li>A bit long = Malignant [No pain]</li>
                <li>Long = Chronic inflammation [Less pain]</li>
                <li>Long = Benign [No pain]</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Progression
          <ul>
            <li>Progressive
              <ol>
                <li>Very rapid = Inflammatory</li>
                <li>Rapidly = Malignant</li>
                <li>Slowly = Benign</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Regressive (inflammatory)</li>
            <li>Static</li>
            <li>Static &acirc;&dagger;&rsquo; Rapid [Benign
              &acirc;&dagger;&rsquo; Malignant]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Aggravating Factors
          <ul>
            <li>Darkness</li>
            <li>Heat</li>
            <li>Pressure</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Relieving Factors</li>
        <ul>
          <li>light</li>
          <li>Pressure</li>
          <li>Rest</li>
        </ul>
        <li>Associated Symptoms: Patient focuses on pain, ask about other
          symptoms
          <ul>
            <li>Pain / headache</li>
            <ul>
              <li>No - </li>
              <ul>
                <li>Subconjunctival Hemorrhage</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Yes</li>
              <ul>
                <li>Glaucoma</li>
              </ul>
            </ul>
            <li>Nausea Vomiting</li>
            <li>Blurred vision</li>
            <li>Fever</li>
            <li>Interfering with movement</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <h4><br>
      </h4>
      <h4><br>
      </h4>
      <h4><br>
      </h4>
      <h4><br>
      </h4>
      <h4>2<sup>ND</sup> COMPLAINT: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>EYE PAIN / HEAD PAIN </strong>(Related
        to Ophthalmic Conditions)</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>SITE (S):
          <ul>
            <li>Where exactly is the pain located?
              <ul>
                <li>Is it in <b>one </b>eye (unilateral) or</li>
                <li><b><u>both </u></b>eyes (bilateral)?</li>
                <li>Is the pain felt </li>
                <ul>
                  <li>within the eye itself, </li>
                  <li>around the eye (periorbital), or </li>
                  <li>more like a headache?</li>
                </ul>
                <li>If headache, is it localized?
                  <ul>
                    <li>Frontal?</li>
                    <li>Temporal? (<u>Giant Cell </u>if temporal, especially in
                      older adults)</li>
                    <li>Occipital?</li>
                    <li>Generalized?</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Is it a surface pain (like something in the eye) or a deep,
                  aching pain?</li>
                <li>Can you point to the exact spot of maximum pain? (e.g.,
                  specific area of sclera for <u>Scleritis</u>)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>ONSET (O):
          <ul>
            <li>Sudden? (e.g., after trauma, acute angle closure <u>Glaucoma</u>)</li>
            <li>Gradual over hours/days/weeks?</li>
            <li>Was there anything specific that seemed to trigger the pain?
              (e.g., injury, bright light exposure, prolonged reading, specific
              activity)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>DURATION (D):
          <ul>
            <li>How long have you been experiencing this pain? (Hours, days,
              weeks, months)</li>
            <li>&Acirc;&plusmn; Painlessness (This section from your original
              HTML seems more relevant to characterizing a *lesion/swelling*
              rather than pain itself. For pain, we'd focus on its
              presence/absence/fluctuation.)
              <ol>
                <li>Short = Inflammatory [Pain]</li>
                <li>A bit long = Malignant [No pain]</li>
                <li>Long = Chronic inflammation [Less pain]</li>
                <li>Long = Benign [No pain]</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>AGGRAVATING/RELIEVING FACTORS (A/R):
          <ul>
            <li>Aggravating Factors: What makes the pain worse?
              <ul>
                <li>Eye movement? (Consider: <u>Optic Neuritis</u>, Scleritis)</li>
                <li>Bright lights (photophobia)?</li>
                <li>Darkness or dim light? (Consider: Acute Angle Closure <u>Glaucoma</u>
                  - AACG)</li>
                <li>Reading or close work?</li>
                <li>Touching or pressure on the eye/head?</li>
                <li>Heat or cold?</li>
                <li>Bending over or straining?</li>
                <li>Specific times of day?</li>
                <ul>
                  <li>Morning -Intracranial hypertension</li>
                </ul>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Relieving Factors: What makes the pain better or go away?
              <ul>
                <li>Resting the eyes?</li>
                <li>Dark room / avoiding light?</li>
                <li>Pain medications (OTC or prescribed)? Which ones and do they
                  help?</li>
                <li>Cold or warm compresses?</li>
                <li>Specific positions?</li>
                <li>Does pressure on the eye relieve or worsen it?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <br>
        <li>CHARACTER/TYPE (C):
          <ul>
            <li>How would you describe the pain? (Ask patient to use their own
              words, then offer prompts if needed)
              <ul>
                <li>Sharp, stabbing, shooting?</li>
                <li>Dull, aching, throbbing?</li>
                <li>Burning, gritty, foreign body sensation?</li>
                <li>Pressure-like, tight band? (Consider: <u>Glaucoma</u> if
                  pressure-like headache)</li>
                <li>Boring?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>RADIATION (R):
          <ul>
            <li>Does the pain spread or radiate anywhere else?
              <ul>
                <li>To the other eye?</li>
                <li>To the temple, jaw, neck?</li>
                <li>Around the head?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>ASSOCIATED SYMPTOMS (A): <br>
          <ul>
            <li><b>Visual Changes:</b>
              <ul>
                <li><u>Blurred vision</u>? (Sudden or gradual?)</li>
                <li>Seeing halos around lights? (Consider: AACG)</li>
                <li>Loss of vision (partial or complete)?</li>
                <li>Floaters or flashes of light?</li>
                <li>Double vision (diplopia)?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>Eye Appearance:</b>
              <ul>
                <li><u>Redness</u> of the eye? (Localized or diffuse?)</li>
                <li>Watering or discharge from the eye? (Nature of discharge:
                  watery, mucoid, purulent)</li>
                <li>Swelling of the eyelids or around the eye?</li>
                <li>Pupil changes noticed by patient?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>Systemic Symptoms:</b>
              <ul>
                <li><u>Nausea and/or Vomiting</u>? (Common with AACG, migraine)</li>
                <li><u>Fever</u>, chills? (Suggests infection)</li>
                <li>Headache (if primary complaint is eye pain, and vice versa)?</li>
                <li>Photophobia (sensitivity to light)?</li>
                <li>Phonophobia (sensitivity to sound)?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><b>Symptoms related to specific conditions:</b>
              <ul>
                <li>Pain or difficulty <u>interfering with eye movement</u>?
                  (Consider: <u>Optic Neuritis</u>, orbital inflammation)</li>
                <li>Symptoms of <u>Polymyalgia Rheumatica</u> (aching/stiffness
                  in shoulders, hips)? (Associated with Giant Cell Arteritis)</li>
                <li>Symptoms of <u>Rheumatoid Arthritis</u> or other autoimmune
                  conditions? (Associated with Scleritis, Uveitis)</li>
                <li>Scalp tenderness, jaw claudication? (Associated with Giant
                  Cell Arteritis)</li>
                <li>Recent cold/sinus infection? (Sinusitis can cause referred
                  eye/head pain)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>PROGRESSION (P):
          <ul>
            <li>How has the pain changed since it first started?
              <ul>
                <li>Is it getting progressively worse, better, or staying the
                  same?</li>
                <li>If it's recurrent, are the episodes becoming more frequent,
                  more severe, or lasting longer? (Consider: <u>Optic Neuritis</u>
                  if recurrent with visual disturbance)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Response to any previous treatments?
              <ol>
                <li>Very rapid = Inflammatory</li>
                <li>Rapidly = Malignant</li>
                <li>Slowly = Benign</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Regressive (inflammatory)</li>
            - This could be relevant if pain is improving
            <li>Static</li>
            <li>Static&nbsp; --&gt; Rapid [Benign --&gt; Malignant]</li>
            - More for lesions/swellings&nbsp;
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>PATTERN (P):
          <ul>
            <li>Is the pain continuous or intermittent?</li>
            <li>If intermittent, is there any pattern to when it occurs? (e.g.,
              time of day, after specific activities)</li>
            <li>Any periods completely free of pain?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>RED FLAGS (R): (Symptoms suggesting a serious underlying cause
          needing urgent attention)
          <ul>
            <li>Sudden, severe, unrelenting eye pain.</li>
            <li>Sudden loss of vision.</li>
            <li>Marked eye redness with a fixed, mid-dilated pupil (suggests
              AACG).</li>
            <li>Photophobia with deep eye ache (suggests iritis/uveitis).</li>
            <li>Proptosis (bulging of the eye).</li>
            <li>Pain with eye movements, especially with vision loss (suggests
              Optic Neuritis).</li>
            <li>New onset headache in an older adult, especially with temporal
              tenderness or jaw claudication (Giant Cell Arteritis).</li>
            <li>Associated neurological deficits (e.g., weakness, numbness,
              diplopia not resolving).</li>
            <li>History of recent eye surgery or trauma with increasing pain.</li>
            <li>Vomiting associated with eye pain/headache.</li>
            <li>Intracranial hypertension </li>
            <ul>
              <li>-Seizures</li>
              <li><br>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>EFFECT ON LIFE (E):
          <ul>
            <li>How is this pain affecting your daily activities (e.g., ability
              to read, work, drive, sleep)?</li>
            <li>Has it caused you to miss work or school?</li>
            <li>How is it affecting your mood or general well-being?</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>SCALE (S) (Severity):
          <ul>
            <li>On a scale of 0 to 10, where 0 is no pain and 10 is the worst
              pain imaginable:
              <ul>
                <li>What number would you give your pain right now?</li>
                <li>What is its average severity?</li>
                <li>What is its severity at its worst?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <ol>
      </ol>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p>5th COMPLAINT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><u>Irritation</u></b>/<b><u>Itching</u></b></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Site:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
          which eye</li>
        <ul>
          <li>one eye</li>
          <ul>
            <ul>
              <li>Episcleritis</li>
            </ul>
          </ul>
          <li>both eye</li>
        </ul>
        <li>Onset: When did patient notice&nbsp;
          <ul>
            <li>Gradual</li>
            <li>Sudden (after trauma)</li>
            <ul>
              <ul>
                <li>Sub conjunctival hemorrhage</li>
              </ul>
            </ul>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Duration
          <ul>
            <li>&Acirc;&plusmn; Painlessness
              <ol>
                <li>Short = Inflammatory [Pain]</li>
                <li>A bit long = Malignant [No pain]</li>
                <li>Long = Chronic inflammation [Less pain]</li>
                <li>Long = Benign [No pain]</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Progression
          <ul>
            <li>Progressive
              <ol>
                <li>Very rapid = Inflammatory</li>
                <li>Rapidly = Malignant</li>
                <li>Slowly = Benign</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Regressive (inflammatory)</li>
            <li>Static</li>
            <li>Static &acirc;&dagger;&rsquo; Rapid [Benign
              &acirc;&dagger;&rsquo; Malignant]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Aggravating Factors
          <ul>
            <li>Darkness</li>
            <li>Heat</li>
            <li>Pressure</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Relieving Factors</li>
        <ul>
          <li>light</li>
          <li>Pressure</li>
          <li>Rest</li>
        </ul>
        <li>Associated Symptoms: <br>
          <ul>
            <li>Pain / headache</li>
            <li>Discharge</li>
            <li>Nausea&nbsp; Vomiting</li>
            <li>Blurred vision</li>
            <li>Fever</li>
            <ul>
              <li>Severe bacterial Conjunctivits</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Interfering with movement</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p></p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <h4>6th COMPLAINT: &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;
        LOSS/&nbsp; BLURRY VISION</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>site</li>
        <ol>
          <li>One eye</li>
          <li>both eyes</li>
          <li>field</li>
        </ol>
        <li>Onset</li>
        <ol>
          <li>sudden</li>
          <ol>
            <li>Retinal detachment</li>
            <li>Optic Neuritis</li>
            <li>C/BRAO</li>
          </ol>
          <li>Gradual</li>
          <ol>
            <li>Cataract</li>
            <li>Myopia</li>
            <li>Hypermetropia</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Duration</li>
        <ol>
          <li>hours</li>
          <li>days</li>
          <li>weeks</li>
          <li>moths</li>
          <ol>
            <li>cataract</li>
          </ol>
          <li>years</li>
        </ol>
        <li>Aggrevating factors</li>
        <ol>
          <li>light</li>
          <li>Dark</li>
          <ol>
            <li>Retinitis pigmentosa</li>
            <li>many other optics associated disorders</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Relieving factor</li>
        <ol>
          <li>better with age?</li>
          <li><br>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <li>Character / type</li>
        <ol>
          <li>near</li>
          <li>far</li>
          <li>colour</li>
          <li><br>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <li>Radiation - there wont be any </li>
        <li>Associated </li>
        <ol>
          <li>scratches to car</li>
          <ol>
            <li>bump into the wall</li>
          </ol>
          <li>pain</li>
          <ol>
            <li>No - cataract</li>
            <li>Yes</li>
          </ol>
          <li>haloes</li>
          <li>floaters</li>
          <li>Stroke Sx?</li>
          <ol>
            <li>Amurosis fugax</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>Progression</li>
        <ol>
          <li>Reccurent</li>
          <ol>
            <li>Optic Neuritis</li>
          </ol>
        </ol>
        <li>pattern</li>
        <ol>
          <li>peripheral loss of vision</li>
          <ol>
            <li>~ Open Glaucoma</li>
            <li><br>
            </li>
          </ol>
          <li>Central loss</li>
          <ol>
