    <h2></h2>
    <h2>Local Examination:</h2>
    <p> remove the glasses/ contacts</p>
    <p><strong>On Inspection with torch light:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li> <strong>Head Posture:</strong><br>
        Any abnormal posture due to strabismus or ptosis. </li>
      <li> <strong>Face:</strong><br>
        Symmetry maintained or not, any asymmetry, facial palsy, herpes zoster,
        swelling, etc. </li>
    </ol>
    <strong>Eye:</strong> <br>
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>Parameter</th>
          <th>Right Eye (RE)</th>
          <th>Left Eye (LE)</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Eye Brows</strong><br>
            Check for elevation, loss, depigmentation.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Orbits</strong><br>
            Cellulitis, fracture signs.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Eyeballs</strong><br>
            Position, movements, size/shape.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Eyelids</strong><br>
            Position, margin, lashes, glands, puncta.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Lacrimal Apparatus</strong><br>
            Swelling, redness, fistula, size, etc.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Conjunctiva</strong><br>
            Congestion, growths, spots (size, colour, site).</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Sclera</strong><br>
            Episcleritis, scleritis, staphyloma, foreign bodies, pigment.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Cornea</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Size (Normal ~11&acirc;&euro;&ldquo;12mm)</li>
              <li>Curvature (conical, globular)</li>
              <li>Transparency &amp; opacities</li>
              <ul>
                <ul>
                  <li>Arcus senilis</li>
                  <li>KF rings</li>
                </ul>
              </ul>
              <li>Surface (window reflex)</li>
              <li>Sensation (cotton wisp)</li>
              <li>Anomalies (ulcer, synechiae, FB, vascularisation, KPs)</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Anterior Chamber</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Depth (Normal ~2.5mm)</li>
              <li>Contents (flare, hypopyon, subluxated lens, ACIOL)</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Iris</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Colour</li>
              <li>Pattern (crypts/elevations)</li>
              <li>Synechiae</li>
              <li>Iridodialysis, iridodonesis</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Pupil</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Size (anisocoria)</li>
              <ul>
                <li>Normal</li>
                <li>Dilated</li>
                <ul>
                  <li><br>
                  </li>
                  <li>Acute angle closure</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Small</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Shape</li>
              <ul>
                <li>Normal</li>
                <li>Unequal</li>
                <li>Round</li>
                <li>Vertical</li>
                <li>Horizontal</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Margin (pseudoexfoliation)</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td> <strong>Pupil Reaction:</strong><br>
            <ol>
              <li> Reaction:</li>
              <ol>
                <li>If direct and </li>
                <li>consensual reflexes </li>
                <li><br>
                </li>
                <li>&nbsp;reacting to light or not, any</li>
                <ol>
                  <li>&nbsp;sluggish reaction or </li>
                  <li>RAPD. </li>
                </ol>
              </ol>
              <li>Accommodation and </li>
              <li>psychosensory reflex also tested. </li>
            </ol>
          </td>
          <td><br>
            <br>
            <br>
            <br>
            <br>
            <br>
            RAPD - Optic neuritis<br>
            <br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td> <strong>Lens:</strong><br>
            1) Colour: <br>
            <ol>
              <li>Jet Black (Aphakia), </li>
              <li>Shimmering light reflex (Pseudophakia), </li>
              <li>Grey white (Immature cataract), </li>
              <li>Pearly white (Mature cataract), </li>
              <li>Milky white (Hypermature cataract), </li>
              <li> Greenish/Yellow/Amber/Brown/Black (Nuclear Sclerosis)</li>
            </ol>
            <br>
            2) Iris Shadow: Seen in immature cataract<br>
            3) Position: Any dislocation or subluxation<br>
            4) Purkinje images: 4 (Clear lens), 2 (Aphakia), 3 (Mature cataract)
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <h3>Visual Acuity</h3>
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Visual Acuity</strong><br>
            <ol>
              <li>far vision</li>
              <ol>
                <li>Snellen</li>
                <ol>
                  <li>large chart at 6 m</li>
                </ol>
                <ol>
                  <li>small chart at 6 ft</li>
                </ol>
                <li>CF method from 6m,</li>
                <li>&nbsp;then HM, </li>
                <li>then PL/</li>
                <li>NPL.</li>
              </ol>
              <li>Near vision</li>
              <li>Colour vision</li>
              <ol>
                <li>ishihara charts</li>
              </ol>
            </ol>
            <div class="video-container">
              <iframe width="1520" height="864" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/_HwWfnB0nBg" title="Visual Field Examination by Dr Ankur #GotAspirEd" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Visual Field <br>
            </strong>tation.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Blind Spot <br>
            </strong>can skip if peripheral field defects.</td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td> <strong>Fundus:</strong><br>
            Checked for posterior segment pathologies.<br>
            Do <em>not </em>use <em>drops</em>!!! in Closure <em>Glaucoma</em>!
            <h5>FUNDOSCOPY PROTOCOL</h5>

            <div class="video-container">
              <iframe width="908" height="500" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/SiuyE7w0lUc" title="How to use an Ophthalmoscope; #GotAspirEd" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
            <br>

            <div class="video-container">
              <iframe width="1520" height="864" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/vWENp_B8vn4" title="Fundoscopy Examination by Dr Ankur #GotAspirEd" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>

            <p><em>Ensure appropriate setting (dimmed room if possible), patient
                comfort, and proper ophthalmoscope use (correct lens,
                appropriate distance). Examine both eyes, comparing findings.
                Start with the patient looking straight ahead, then ask them to
                look in different directions to visualize different quadrants of
                the retina. Finally, ask the patient to look directly at the
                light to view the macula.</em></p>
            <h5>Assess the Red Reflex:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Presence and Character:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Is the red reflex present </li>
                  <li>symmetrical in both eyes?</li>
                  <li>Is it bright and orange-red, or dull/absent?</li>
                  <li>Are there any </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>opacities, </li>
                    <li>dark spots, or </li>
                    <li>white reflections (leukocoria) within the red reflex?</li>
                  </ul>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><em>Potential Abnormalities:</em>
                <ul>
                  <li>Absent or diminished red reflex: </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Cataracts, </li>
                    <li>vitreous hemorrhage, </li>
                    <li>large retinal detachment, </li>
                    <li>severe corneal opacity.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Leukocoria (white reflex): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Retinoblastoma (in children), </li>
                    <li>cataract, </li>
                    <li>Coats' disease, </li>
                    <li>persistent fetal vasculature.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Dark spots: </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Floaters, </li>
                    <li>localized opacities.</li>
                  </ul>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Examine the Optic Disc (Optic Nerve Head):</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Colour:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Normally pinkish-orange </li>
                  <li>or </li>
                  <li>yellowish-orange.</li>
                  <li><br>
                  </li>
                  <li>Is it pale (atrophy) or </li>
                  <li>hyperemic (swollen/inflamed)?</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Contour / Margins:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Are the disc margins </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>sharp and distinct, or </li>
                    <li>blurred/indistinct?</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Is there elevation of the disc (papilledema)?</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Cup-to-Disc Ratio (C/D Ratio):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Assess the size of the central physiological cup relative
                    to the entire disc diameter (e.g., 0.3).</li>
                  <li>Is the cup symmetrically sized between the two eyes?</li>
                  <li>Is there cupping (enlargement of the cup, &gt;0.5-0.6) or
                    notching?</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Spontaneous Venous Pulsation (SVP):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Often present in healthy individuals (subtle pulsation of
                    retinal veins as they cross the disc).</li>
                  <li>Absence can be normal but new absence in the presence of
                    other signs might be significant.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><em>Potential Abnormalities:</em>
                <ul>
                  <li>Papilledema (swollen disc, blurred margins, elevated): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Raised intracranial pressure.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Optic atrophy (pale disc): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Previous optic nerve damage, </li>
                    <li>glaucoma, </li>
                    <li>ischemia.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Glaucomatous cupping (increased C/D ratio, notching): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>&nbsp;Glaucoma.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Optic disc drusen: </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Hyaline bodies, </li>
                    <li>can mimic papilledema.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Optic neuritis: Swollen, hyperemic disc, often with pain
                    on eye movement and vision loss.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Examine the Retinal Vessels (Arteries and Veins):</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Artery-to-Vein (A/V) Ratio:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Normally veins are slightly larger than arteries (A/V
                    ratio approx. 2:3 or 4:5).</li>
                  <li>Is there arterial narrowing (attenuation) or venous
                    dilation?</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Arterial Light Reflex:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Observe the central light streak on arteries.</li>
                  <li>Is it normal, broadened ("copper wiring"), or obscured
                    ("silver wiring")?</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Arteriovenous (AV) Crossing Changes:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Where arteries cross veins, observe for:
                    <ul>
                      <li>Nipping/constriction of the vein.</li>
                      <li>Banking/deflection of the vein.</li>
                      <li>Salus' sign (deflection of vein).</li>
                      <li>Gunn's sign (tapering of vein on either side of
                        crossing).</li>
                    </ul>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Vessel Tortuosity:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Are the vessels abnormally twisted or tortuous?</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Pulsations:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Arterial pulsations are usually abnormal (unless very low
                    IOP).Note spontaneous venous pulsations at the disc.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><em>Potential Abnormalities:</em>
                <ul>
                  <li>Arterial narrowing, AV nipping, copper/silver wiring: </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>&nbsp;Hypertensive retinopathy.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Venous dilation and tortuosity, retinal hemorrhages
                    (flame-shaped, dot/blot): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Diabetic retinopathy, </li>
                    <li>retinal vein occlusion.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Emboli (e.g., Hollenhorst plaques): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Retinal artery occlusion.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <li>Neovascularization (new abnormal vessel growth): </li>
                  <ul>
                    <li>&nbsp;Proliferative diabetic retinopathy, </li>
                    <li>vein occlusions.</li>
                  </ul>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Examine the Retinal Background / General Fundus:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Colour and Pigmentation:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Note the general colour (orange-red) and any variations in
                    pigmentation.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Retinal Nerve Fibre Layer (RNFL):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Subtle striations radiating from the optic disc, best seen
                    with green (red-free) light.</li>
                  <li>Look for defects or thinning (can indicate glaucoma or
                    optic neuropathy).</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Haemorrhages:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Type: </li>
                  <li>Flame-shaped (nerve fibre layer), </li>
                  <li>dot/blot (deeper retinal layers), </li>
                  <li>pre-retinal (boat-shaped).</li>
                  <li><br>
                  </li>
                  <li>Location and extent.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Exudates:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Hard exudates: Yellowish, waxy deposits (lipid residue
                    from leaky vessels).</li>
                  <li>Cotton wool spots (soft exudates): White, fluffy patches
                    (axoplasmic debris from retinal ischemia).</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Other Lesions:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Drusen: Yellowish deposits (associated with age-related
                    macular degeneration if in macula).</li>
                  <li>Pigmentary changes, scarring.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><em>Potential Abnormalities:</em>
                <ul>
                  <li>Haemorrhages, exudates, microaneurysms: Diabetic
                    retinopathy, hypertensive retinopathy, vein occlusions.</li>
                  <li>Retinal detachment: Retina appears elevated, undulating,
                    sometimes with a visible tear.</li>
                  <li>Choroiditis/Retinitis: Inflammatory patches.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Examine the Macula and Fovea:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Location:</strong> Typically temporal to the optic
                disc (approx. 2 disc diameters away).</li>
              <li><strong>Foveal Reflex:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>A small, bright pinpoint light reflex at the center of the
                    fovea (may be absent in older individuals or with macular
                    pathology).</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>Appearance:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>The macula is a darker, avascular area.</li>
                  <li>Look for any abnormalities: Haemorrhages, exudates,
                    drusen, pigmentary changes, swelling, cysts.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><em>Potential Abnormalities:</em>
                <ul>
                  <li>Age-related Macular Degeneration (AMD): Drusen, pigmentary
                    changes, neovascularization, haemorrhage.</li>
                  <li>Diabetic Maculopathy: Exudates, macular edema.</li>
                  <li>Macular hole.</li>
                  <li>Cherry-red spot: Central retinal artery occlusion.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Examine the Vitreous (if visible):</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Look for floaters, haziness, or cells.</li>
              <li><em>Potential Abnormalities:</em> Vitreous haemorrhage,
                uveitis (inflammatory cells).</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Document Findings:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Systematically record findings for each eye, using diagrams if
                helpful.</li>
              <li>Note any asymmetries between the eyes.</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
          <td>
            <ol>
              <li>Drusen</li>
              <ol>
                <li>Dry ARMD</li>
              </ol>
            </ol>
            <br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <h4>On Palpation:</h4>
    <table>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td>Right Eye (RE)</td>
          <td>Left Eye (LE)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td> <strong>IOP:</strong><br>
            By digital tonometry using index fingers of both hands, perform
            fluctuation test on downward gaze beyond the tarsal plate. Mention
            the finding:
            <ol>
              <li>firm (normal), </li>
              <li>soft, or</li>
              <li>hard.</li>
            </ol>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td> <strong>Regurgitation On Pressure over Lacrimal Sac (ROPLAS):</strong><br>
            Press over the medial canthus and look for regurgitation. Mention if
            positive/negative with the nature of the secretion.
            <ol>
              <li>Positive/negative</li>
              <li>Nature of secretion</li>
            </ol>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td> <strong>Swelling:</strong><br>
            If there is a swelling in lid/at medial canthus, palpate to confirm
            the findings on inspection: size, shape, surface, adhesion to
            underlying structures or overlying skin, plane of origin, local rise
            of temperature, tenderness, mobility, reducibility, etc. </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
          <td><br>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
